<section id="evaluation-2" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="evaluation-2">Evaluation</h2>
<p>The first histogram is our baseline contentâbased recommender (rating + sentiment + length + category only), and the second histogram is the enhanced recommender after we injected our logisticâregression probability feature.</p>
<p>Plot 1</p>
<ul>
<li>(baseline) shows almost all similarities clustered in the negative/nearâzero region, with only a tiny spike up near +1.0.</li>
</ul>
<p>Plot 2</p>
<ul>
<li>(with our prob_neg feature) has a visibly fatter rightâhand tail (more items in the +0.2 to +1.0 range), meaning more candidates are judged âsimilar.â</li>
</ul>
<p>Since a richer positive tail generally translates to moreâand potentially betterârecommendation candidates, Plot 2 (the second one) demonstrates the improved recommender.</p>
</section>
</section>
<section id="conclusion" class="level1">
<h1>Conclusion</h1>
<section id="sentiment-classification" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="sentiment-classification">Sentiment Classification</h2>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Supervised vs.Â LexiconâBased</strong> Our logisticâregression model achieves <strong>85.5% accuracy</strong> (Kappaâ¯=â¯0.074) versus Syuzhetâs <strong>82.8% accuracy</strong> (Kappaâ¯ââ¯0) .</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Implication:</strong> A domainâspecific, supervised classifier better captures the nuanced language of Amazon reviews than a generic lexicon.</li>
</ul></li>
<li><p><strong>What we should do differently:</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li><strong>Adopt a supervised pipeline</strong> (e.g.Â logistic regression or more powerful models like random forests/gradient boosting) trained on labeled historical reviews instead of relying solely on offâtheâshelf sentiment lexicons.</li>
<li><strong>Periodically retrain</strong> our model as product categories and customer language evolve to prevent performance degradation.</li>
</ol></li>
<li><p><strong>Quantifiable improvement:</strong> Switching to our supervised model yields a <strong>+2.7â¯pp lift in accuracy</strong> on our test setâabout <strong>3 more correctly classified reviews per 100</strong>, improving the quality of downstream personalization .</p></li>
</ul>
</section>
<section id="feature-engineering-for-recommendation" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="feature-engineering-for-recommendation">Feature Engineering for Recommendation</h2>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Baseline vs.Â Enhanced Recommender</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Baseline</strong> (rating + sentiment label + review length + category): similarity scores cluster near zero.</li>
<li><strong>Enhanced</strong> (adds the supervised-modelâs <code>prob_neg</code>): exhibits a âfatterâ right tail in cosineâsimilarity (more items scoring &gt;â¯0.2), meaning moreâand potentially higherâqualityâcandidates are surfaced .</li>
</ul></li>
<li><p><strong>What we should do differently:</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li><strong>Include supervised sentiment probability (<code>prob_neg</code>)</strong> as a feature in our contentâbased similarity metric.</li>
<li><strong>Experiment with feature weighting</strong>, giving more weight to <code>prob_neg</code> when computing cosine similarity to further amplify its impact.</li>
<li><strong>Incorporate additional signals</strong> such as collaborativeâfiltering embeddings or behavioral coâclick data, assuming interaction logs are available.</li>
</ol></li>
<li><p><strong>Quantifiable improvement:</strong> From our histograms, the proportion of candidate pairs with similarity &gt;â¯0.2 roughly <strong>doubles</strong>, potentially yielding <strong>2Ã more relevant recommendations</strong> per query .</p></li>
</ul>
</section>
<section id="domainrelevant-insights-for-decisionmakers" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="domainrelevant-insights-for-decisionmakers">DomainâRelevant Insights for DecisionâMakers</h2>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Actionable Choices Within Our Control:</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li><strong>Model selection &amp; retraining cadence:</strong> allocate resources to retrain our supervised sentiment models on fresh review data.</li>
<li><strong>Feature prioritization:</strong> invest in pipelines that compute and store prediction probabilities (not just labels) so they can be reused across downstream applications.</li>
<li><strong>Similarity thresholds:</strong> tune the cosineâsimilarity cutoff in production to balance recommendation volume with relevance.</li>
</ol></li>
<li><p><strong>Improvements &amp; Quantification:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Measure <strong>Precision@K</strong> (e.g., fraction of truly similar products among topâ¯5 recommendations) before and after injecting <code>prob_neg</code>; we can target a <strong>5â10â¯pp lift</strong> in precision if our histogram gains translate to real relevance.</li>
<li>A/Bâtest user engagement metrics (e.g., clickâthrough rate on recommended products) with an initial hypothesis of a <strong>10â20% lift</strong> in CTR based on our doubled positiveâsimilarity pool.</li>
</ul></li>
<li><p><strong>Caveat on Demographics:</strong> Differences in review length or word usage across rating groups are <strong>predictive</strong> but not directly actionable. We should focus on <strong>controllable inputs</strong>âmodel choice, feature set, and similarity scoringârather than immutable reviewer characteristics.</p></li>
</ul>
</section>
<section id="reallife-applications-of-our-recommender-system" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="reallife-applications-of-our-recommender-system">RealâLife Applications of Our Recommender System</h2>
<p>In practice, we can embed our enhanced recommender into an eâcommerce platform to drive personalized shopping experiences. By ranking products not only on historical ratings but also on nuanced sentiment probabilities, we surface items that align more closely with what customers care about. This leads to higher engagementâmeasured by addâtoâcart rates and conversionâand supports crossâselling by recommending complementary products with positive sentiment signals. For example, a customer looking at a âwireless keyboardâ may receive suggestions for a matching âgaming mouseâ that other users praised in reviews. Over time, as we retrain on fresh data and refine our similarity thresholds, we can continuously boost recommendation relevance and, ultimately, incremental revenue for the platform.</p>
</section>
</section>

      let selectedAnnoteEl;

      const selectCodeLines = (annoteEl) => {
        const doc = window.document;

        const lineIds = lines.map((line) => {
          return targetCell + "-" + line;
        })
        let top = null;
        let height = null;
        let parent = null;
        if (lineIds.length > 0) {
            //compute the position of the single el (top and bottom and make a div)
            const el = window.document.getElementById(lineIds[0]);
            top = el.offsetTop;
            height = el.offsetHeight;
            parent = el.parentElement.parentElement;
          if (lineIds.length > 1) {
            const lastEl = window.document.getElementById(lineIds[lineIds.length - 1]);
            const bottom = lastEl.offsetTop + lastEl.offsetHeight;
            height = bottom - top;
          }
          if (top !== null && height !== null && parent !== null) {
            // cook up a div (if necessary) and position it 
            let div = window.document.getElementById("code-annotation-line-highlight");
            if (div === null) {
              div = window.document.createElement("div");
              div.setAttribute("id", "code-annotation-line-highlight");
              div.style.position = 'absolute';
              parent.appendChild(div);
            }
            div.style.top = top - 2 + "px";
            div.style.height = height + 4 + "px";
            div.style.left = 0;
            let gutterDiv = window.document.getElementById("code-annotation-line-highlight-gutter");
            if (gutterDiv === null) {

              gutterDiv.setAttribute("id", "code-annotation-line-highlight-gutter");

    function throttle(fn, ms) {
    let throttle = false;
    let timer;
      return (...args) => {
        if(!throttle) { // first call gets through
            fn.apply(this, args);
            throttle = true;
        } else { // all the others get throttled
            if(timer) clearTimeout(timer); // cancel #2
            timer = setTimeout(() => {
              fn.apply(this, args);

            }, ms);
        }
      };
